{"title_page": "Jesse Welles", "text_new": "{{for|the vlogger|Jesse Wellens}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jesse Welles Nathan\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Jesse Welles\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1946|4|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, Artist\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| honorific_suffix   = \n| alt                = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| baptised           = \n| disappeared_date   = \n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| years_active       = 1971-1988\n(Actress)\n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| net_worth          = \n| height             = \n| height_m           = \n| height_cm          = \n| height_ft          = \n| height_in          = \n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| criminal_charges   = \n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Stephen Nathan|11 January 1976}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = 3\n| parents            = \n| mother             = \n| father             = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| honours            = \n| website            = https://jwnathan.com/\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n| image_upright      = \n| landscape          = yes\n| burial_place       = \n| burial_coordinates = \n}}\n\n'''Jesse Welles Nathan''' (born 16 April 1946) is a former actress, perhaps known best for her voice work in the animated classic ''[[Wizards (film)|Wizards]]'' (1977).<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|id=0919934|name=Jesse Welles}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWelles provided voices for three animated films directed by [[Ralph Bakshi]]: ''[[Coonskin (film)|Coonskin]]'' (1975) as Marrigold and Miss America; ''[[Wizards (film)|Wizards]]'' (1977) as Elinore; and ''[[Hey Good Lookin' (film)|Hey Good Lookin']]'' (1982) as Eva.<ref name=\"Maltin2011\">{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|title=Leonard Maltin's 2012 Movie Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6EgPDierNGUC&pg=PA606|accessdate=2012-04-20|date=2011-11-24|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780452289789|pages=606\u2013}}</ref>\n\nWelles played a lead role in three episodes of ''[[The Rockford Files]]'': \"Roundabout\" (season 1, episode 23); \"2 Into 5.56 Won't Go\" (season 2, episode 10); and \"A Different Drummer\" (season 5, episode 22). She appeared in season 4 of the sitcom ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]'' as a prostitute who gets romantically involved with Danny, and she was a regular on ''[[Husbands, Wives & Lovers]]''.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0919934/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref>\n\nAfter 1988, Welles left acting and became an artist, and her work has been displayed at various galleries across Southern California, including the Schomburg Gallery. Her art style consists of mixed media with old photos drawn with balloons or vibrant colors.<ref>https://www.artslant.com/global/artists/show/4041-jesse-welles-nathan</ref>\n \n==Film and television roles==\n* ''[[The Return of Count Yorga]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'' (TV series, 1974)\n* ''[[Kojak]]'' (TV series) (1975)\n* ''[[Coonskin (film)|Coonskin]] (film) (1975) <ref>The chuckles and vocal dialogue in ''Wizards'' with \"Ellinore\" sound similar to those for \"Miss America\" (and \"Marrigold\") in ''Coonskin''.</ref>\n* ''[[Switch (TV series)|Switch]]'' (TV series, 1976)\n* ''[[Wizards (film)|Wizards]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Rockford Files]]'' (TV series, 1975-1979)\n* ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' (TV series, 1980)\n* ''[[Hey Good Lookin' (film)|Hey Good Lookin']]'' (1982)\n* ''[[It Takes Two (U.S. TV series)|It Takes Two]]'' (TV series, 1982)\n* ''[[Rhinestone (film)|Rhinestone]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[T.J. Hooker]]'' (TV series) (1985)\n* ''[[Family Ties]]'' (TV series) (1985)\n* ''[[Fame (1982 TV series)|Fame]]'' (TV series, 1986)\n* ''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]'' (TV series, 1988)\n* ''[[Newhart]] (TV series, 1988)\n\n==See also==\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0919934|name=Jesse Welles}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welles, Jesse}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n\n\n{{voice-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the vlogger|Jesse Wellens}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jesse Welles Nathan\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Jesse Welles\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1946|4|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Actor, Artist\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| honorific_suffix   = \n| alt                = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| baptised           = \n| disappeared_date   = \n| disappeared_place  = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments          = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| citizenship        = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| years_active       = 1971-1988\n(Actress)\n| era                = \n| employer           = \n| organization       = \n| agent              = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| style              = \n| home_town          = \n| net_worth          = \n| height             = \n| height_m           = \n| height_cm          = \n| height_ft          = \n| height_in          = \n| television         = \n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| criminal_charges   = \n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Stephen Nathan|January 11, 1976}}\n| partner            = \n| children           = 3\n| parents            = \n| mother             = \n| father             = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| honours            = \n| website            = https://jwnathan.com/\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n| image_upright      = \n| landscape          = yes\n| burial_place       = \n| burial_coordinates = \n}}\n\n'''Jesse Welles Nathan''' (born April 16th, 1946) is a former actress. She provided voices for the animated films ''[[Wizards (film)|Wizards]]'' as Elinore and ''[[Hey Good Lookin' (film)|Hey Good Lookin']]'' as Eva,<ref name=\"Maltin2011\">{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|title=Leonard Maltin's 2012 Movie Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6EgPDierNGUC&pg=PA606|accessdate=20 April 2012|date=2011-11-24|publisher=Penguin|isbn=9780452289789|pages=606\u2013}}</ref> directed by [[Ralph Bakshi]]. She played a lead role in three episodes of ''[[The Rockford Files]]'': \"Roundabout\" (season 1, episode 23), \"2 Into 5.56 Won't Go\" (season 2, episode 10) and \"A Different Drummer\" (season 5, episode 22). She also appeared in season 4 of the sitcom ''[[Soap (TV series)|Soap]]'' as a prostitute who gets romantically involved with Danny, and she was a regular on ''[[Husbands, Wives & Lovers]]''. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0919934/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm</ref> \nShe left acting and became an artist, and her work has been displayed at various galleries across Southern California, including the Schomburg Gallery. Her art style consists of mixed media with old photos drawn with balloons or vibrant colors.\n<ref>https://www.artslant.com/global/artists/show/4041-jesse-welles-nathan</ref>\n \n==Film and television roles==\n* ''[[The Return of Count Yorga]]'' (1971)\n* ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'' (TV series, 1974)\n* ''[[Kojak]]'' (TV series) (1975)\n* ''[[Coonskin (film)|Coonskin]] (film) (1975) <ref>The chuckles and vocal dialogue in Wizards with Ellinore and Miss America (and Marrigold) sound alike</ref>\n* ''[[Switch (TV series)|Switch]]'' (TV series, 1976)\n* ''[[Wizards (film)|Wizards]]'' (1977)\n* ''[[The Rockford Files]]'' (TV series, 1975-1979)\n* ''[[Trapper John, M.D.]]'' (TV series, 1980)\n* ''[[Hey Good Lookin' (film)|Hey Good Lookin']]'' (1982)\n* ''[[It Takes Two (U.S. TV series)|It Takes Two]]'' (TV series, 1982)\n* ''[[Rhinestone (film)|Rhinestone]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[T.J. Hooker]]'' (TV series) (1985)\n* ''[[Family Ties]]'' (TV series) (1985)\n* ''[[Fame (1982 TV series)|Fame]]'' (TV series, 1986)\n* ''[[Hunter (1984 U.S. TV series)|Hunter]]'' (TV series, 1988)\n* ''[[Newhart]] (TV series, 1988)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0919934|name=Jesse Welles}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Welles, Jesse}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n\n\n{{voice-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Albanaco", "label": "safe", "comment": "wiki style; minor clarif; ref req", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesse_Welles"}
{"title_page": "Ravindra Jain", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian composer, lyricist and playback singer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ravindra Jain\n| image              = RavindraJain.jpg\n| alt                = Hindi man with a microphone on a stage in 2015\n| caption            = Jain at the Rajasthan Cinema Awards in 2015\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1944|2|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Aligarh]], India\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2015|10|9|1944|2|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Nagpur]], India\n| spouse             = Divya Jain\n| children           = 1\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Music composer, lyricist, playback singer\n| years_active       = 1971\u20132015\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| signature          = File:91TIH7bAzQL. AC SL1500 ~2.jpg\n}}\n'''Ravindra Jain''' (28 February 1944 \u2013 9 October 2015)<ref>Pandya, Haresh. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/11/arts/music/ravindra-jain-bollywood-film-composer-dies-at-71.html/ \"Ravindra Jain, Bollywood Film Composer, Dies at 71\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', United States, 10 October 2015. Retrieved on 26 March 2019.</ref><ref>''Business Standard''. [https://wap-business--standard-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/current-affairs/bollywood-s-veteran-music-composer-ravindra-jain-dies-at-71-115100901161_1.html?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com&amp_tf=From%20%251%24s&ampshare=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Farticle%2Fcurrent-affairs%2Fbollywood-s-veteran-music-composer-ravindra-jain-dies-at-71-115100901161_1.html/ \"Bollywood's veteran music composer Ravindra Jain dies at 71\"], ''Business  Standard'', India, 9 October 2015. Retrieved on 26 March 2019.</ref> was an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Music Composer]], [[lyricist]], [[Playback Singer]].  He started his career in the early 1970s, composing for hit movies such as ''[[Chor Machaye Shor]]'' (1974), ''[[Geet Gaata Chal]]'' (1975), ''[[Chitchor]]'' (1976) and ''[[Ankhiyon Ke Jharokhon Se]]'' (1978). He composed music for a lot of films and TV shows based on Hindu epics, including [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'' (1987).<ref>{{cite news |title=\u092a\u0941\u0923\u094d\u092f\u0924\u093f\u0925\u093f \u0930\u0935\u0940\u0902\u0926\u094d\u0930 \u091c\u0948\u0928: \u091c\u093f\u0928\u0915\u0947 \u092c\u093f\u0928\u093e \u0930\u093e\u092e\u093e\u092f\u0923 \u0936\u0941\u0930\u0942 \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0939\u094b\u0924\u0940 \u0925\u0940 |url=https://hindi.firstpost.com/special/ravindra-jain-composer-of-ramayan-chitchor-ram-teri-ganga-unknown-facts-trivia-59080.html |accessdate=19 July 2019 |work=Firstpost Hindi |date=9 October 2017}}</ref> He was awarded the [[Padma Shri]], the fourth-highest civilian award of the Republic of India in 2015 for his contribution to arts.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nRavindra Jain was born blind on 28 February 1944 to Pandit Indramani Jain and Kiran Jain as the third child of seven brothers and one sister. He belongs to the [[Jain community]]. His father was a Sanskrit pundit; his mother was a homemaker.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/ravindra-jain-musician/295572|title=Ravindra Jain Profile|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nHis father recognised his talent and sent him to stalwarts like G.L. Jain, Janardhan Sharma and Nathu Ram for formal education in music.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.tentaran.com/ravindra-jain-musician-wonders-music/|title=Ravindra Jain {{!}} Famous Indian Musician - Tentaran|last=Tentaran|date=24 May 2017|website=Tentaran - there's more to life|language=en-US|access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref> At a young age, he started singing bhajans at temples.<ref name=\":2\">Vats, Rohit. [https://hindustantimes.com/bollywood/ravindra-jain-the-man-who-introduced-yesudas-to-us/story-aR6HzA7Pd2RVTdhpokn6oN.html/ \"Ravindra Jain: The man who introduced Yesudas to us\"], ''Hindustan Times'', India. 9 October 2015. Retrieved on 26 March 2019.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n{{expand section|date=November 2019}}\nHis works include ''[[Saudagar (1973 film)|Saudagar]]'', ''[[Chor Machaye Shor]]'', ''[[Chitchor]]'', ''[[Geet Gaata Chal]]'', ''[[Fakira (film)|Fakira]]'', ''[[Ankhiyon Ke Jharokhon Se]]'', ''[[Dulhan Wahi Jo Piya Man Bhaye]]'', ''[[Paheli (1977 film)|Paheli]]'', ''[[Do Jasoos]]'', ''[[Pati Patni Aur Woh]]'', ''[[Insaf Ka Tarazu]]'', ''[[Nadiya Ke Paar (1982 film)|Nadiya Ke Paar]]'', ''[[Ram Teri Ganga Maili]]'' and ''[[Henna (film)|Henna]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> He extensively used [[Yesudas]] and [[Hemlata]] for singing his songs.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> He composed many religious albums in different Indian languages, including [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Malayalam]]. He composed music for several television series. His music for [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s [[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayana]] became iconic.<ref name=\":0\" /> \nSongs of Ramayan Serial were so iconic and epic that it immediately gets Connected to Every citizen who listens it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtubevideoepisode.com/ravindra-jain-songs/|title=Ravindra Jain Songs|last=|first=|date=|website=Youtube Video Episode|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 April 2020}}</ref>\nSome of his most popular works on TV are ''[[Krishna (TV series)|Shri Krishna]]'', ''[[Alif Laila]]'', ''Jai Ganga Maiya'', ''Jai Mahalaxmi'', ''Shree Brahma Vishnu Mahesh'', ''Sai Baba'', ''Jai Maa Durga'', ''[[Jai Hanuman (1997 TV series)|Jai Hanuman]]'' and ''Maha Kavya Mahabharat''.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nJain was married to Divya Jain, with whom he has a son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://filmbandhuup.gov.in/post/ravindra-jain|title=Film Bandhu|website=filmbandhuup.gov.in|access-date=7 October 2019}}</ref> He died in Mumbai on 9 October 2015 because of multiple organ failure.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/11/arts/music/ravindra-jain-bollywood-film-composer-dies-at-71.html|title=Ravindra Jain, Bollywood Film Composer, Dies at 71|last=Pandya|first=Haresh|date=10 October 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=8 November 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nHe was awarded the [[Padma Shri]], the fourth-highest civilian award of the Republic of India in 2015 for his contribution to arts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Jains-steal-the-show-with-7-Padmas/articleshow/46856659.cms|title=Jains steal the show with 7 Padmas|author=TNN|date=9 April 2015|website=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=27 March 2019}}</ref> He received the [[Filmfare Award for Best Music Director|Filmfare Best Music Director award]] for his work in ''[[Ram Teri Ganga Maili]]'' in 1985.<ref>''Filmfare'' [https://www.filmfare.com/awards/filmfare-awards/winners/ \"ALL FILMFARE AWARDS WINNERS\"], ''Filmfare'', India, \u00a92019. Retrieved on 27 March 2019. </ref> Ravindra Jain won many other awards for his contribution to Indian music.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nHis funeral was attended by numerous celebrities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/hema-malini-vishal-bhardwaj-bid-final-farewell-to-ravindra-jain-1230733|title=Hema Malini, Vishal Bhardwaj Bid Final Farewell to Ravindra Jain - NDTV Movies|website=NDTVMovies.com|language=en|access-date=8 November 2019}}</ref>. Prime minister [[Narendra Modi|Modi]] said: \"He will be remembered for his versatile music and fighting spirit.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0415838}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jain, Ravindra}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian composers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian composers]]\n[[Category:Blind musicians]]\n[[Category:Bollywood playback singers]]\n[[Category:Indian male songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Aligarh]]\n[[Category:Indian Jain musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian composer, lyricist and playback singer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ravindra Jain\n| image              = RavindraJain.jpg\n| alt                = Hindi man with a microphone on a stage in 2015\n| caption            = Jain at the Rajasthan Cinema Awards in 2015\n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1944|2|28|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Aligarh]], India\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2015|10|9|1944|2|28|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[Nagpur]], India\n| spouse             = Divya Jain\n| children           = 1\n| nationality        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Music composer, lyricist, playback singer\n| years_active       = 1971\u20132015\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n| signature          = File:91TIH7bAzQL. AC SL1500 ~2.jpg\n}}\n'''Ravindra Jain''' (28 February 1944 \u2013 9 October 2015)<ref>Pandya, Haresh. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/11/arts/music/ravindra-jain-bollywood-film-composer-dies-at-71.html/ \"Ravindra Jain, Bollywood Film Composer, Dies at 71\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', United States, 10 October 2015. Retrieved on 26 March 2019.</ref><ref>''Business Standard''. [https://wap-business--standard-com.cdn.ampproject.org/v/s/wap.business-standard.com/article-amp/current-affairs/bollywood-s-veteran-music-composer-ravindra-jain-dies-at-71-115100901161_1.html?amp_js_v=a2&amp_gsa=1&usqp=mq331AQCCAE%3D#referrer=https%3A%2F