{"title_page": "Don't It Make You Want to Go Home", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\n| cover      = Don't_It_Make_You_Want_to_Go_Home_-_Joe_South.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Joe South]]\n| album      = Don't It Make You Want to Go Home?\n| B-side     = Hearts Desire\n| released   = {{start date|1969|08|}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[Country music|Country]]\n*[[easy listening]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Joe South]]\n| producer   = [[Joe South]]\n| prev_title = Leaning on You\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Walk a Mile in My Shoes]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n\"'''Don't It Make You Want to Go Home'''\" is a 1969 song by [[Joe South]]. South was also producer and arranger of the track, and of its B-side, \"Hearts Desire\". The single was credited to \"Joe South and the Believers\"; the Believers included his brother Tommy South and his sister-in-law Barbara South.\n\n\"Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\" became a hit on the Pop, Country, and Adult Contemporary charts of both the U.S. and Canada.  It was also a Top 20 hit in Australia.<ref name=\"Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992\">{{cite book|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|format=doc|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6|title-link=Kent Music Report}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1969)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref>[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/19691122.html Go-Set National Top 40, 22 November 1969]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Adult Contemporary\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Country\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19691018.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles, October 18, 1969 |access-date=March 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330211252/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19691018.html |archive-date=March 30, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n|}\n\n==Brook Benton cover==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Brook Benton]]\n| album      = Homestyle\n| B-side     = [[I've Gotta Be Me]]\n| released   = {{start date|1970|05|}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[R&B]]\n*[[easy listening]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Cotillion Records|Cotillion]]\n| writer     = [[Joe South]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[My Way]]\n| prev_year  = 1970\n| next_title = Shoes\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n[[Brook Benton]] covered \"Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\" in 1970.  It is a track on his ''Homestyle'' LP. Benton's rendition reached #45 in the U.S. and #41 in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3808&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3808.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3808|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1970-07-04 |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>  His version also reached number four on the U.S. Adult Contemporary chart.\n\nThe B-side, \"[[I've Gotta Be Me]],\" was taken from his previous album, ''Brook Benton Today''.\n\n===Chart history===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1970)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref>[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/19691108.html Go-Set National Top 40, November 8, 1969]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|13\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3808&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3808.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3808|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=1970-07-04 |accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[R&B]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|-\n|U.S. [[Cash Box (magazine)|''Cash Box'']] Top 100<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19700627.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles, June 27, 1970 |access-date=June 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150608162206/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/70s_files/19700627.html |archive-date=June 8, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|48\n|-\n|}\n\n==Other cover versions==\n[[Bobby Bare]] recorded the song on his 1970 LP, ''This Is Bare Country''.  It has also been covered by [[Jerry Reed]], [[Al Green]], [[Mel Tillis]], [[Johnny Rodriguez]], [[Glen Campbell]], Dave Kirby, [[Henson Cargill]], and [[The Persuasions]].\n\n==TV performances==\nSouth performed the song with [[Johnny Cash]], [[June Carter Cash]] and [[George Lindsey]] on ''[[The Johnny Cash Show (TV series)|The Johnny Cash Show]]'' in October of 1970.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yBPBWLmF-W8]\n\n[[Glen Campbell]] and [[John Denver]] performed \"Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\" on the ''Thank God I'm A Country Boy'' variety special in 1977.[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hcmnS_2buGA]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.songlyrics.com/joe-south/don-t-it-make-you-want-to-go-home-lyrics/ Lyrics of this song]\n* {{YouTube|AirBbS4R7Z0|Listen to \"Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\"}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Don't It Make You Want to Go Home}}\n[[Category:1969 songs]]\n[[Category:1969 singles]]\n[[Category:1970 singles]]\n[[Category:Joe South songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Bare songs]]\n[[Category:Brook Benton songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Joe South]]\n[[Category:Capitol Records singles]]\n[[Category:American soft rock songs]] \n[[Category:Rhythm and blues ballads]]\n[[Category:1960s ballads]]\n\n{{1960s-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\n| cover      = Don't_It_Make_You_Want_to_Go_Home_-_Joe_South.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Joe South]]\n| album      = Don't It Make You Want to Go Home?\n| B-side     = Hearts Desire\n| released   = {{start date|1969|08|}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[Country music|Country]]\n*[[easy listening]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n| writer     = [[Joe South]]\n| producer   = [[Joe South]]\n| prev_title = Leaning on You\n| prev_year  = 1969\n| next_title = [[Walk a Mile in My Shoes]]\n| next_year  = 1970\n}}\n\n\"'''Don't It Make You Want to Go Home'''\" is a 1969 song by [[Joe South]]. South was also producer and arranger of the track, and of its B-side, \"Hearts Desire\". The single was credited to \"Joe South and the Believers\"; the Believers included his brother Tommy South and his sister-in-law Barbara South.\n\n\"Don't It Make You Want to Go Home\" became a hit on the Pop, Country, and Adult Contemporary charts of both the U.S. and Canada.  It was also a Top 20 hit in Australia.<ref name=\"Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992\">{{cite book|title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992|format=doc|last=Kent|first=David|authorlink=David Kent (historian)|publisher=Australian Chart Book, St Ives, N.S.W |year=1993|isbn=0-646-11917-6|title-link=Kent Music Report}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1969)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia (''[[Go-Set]]'')<ref>[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1969/19691122.html Go-Set National Top 40, 22 November 1969]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Top Singles\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Adult Contemporary\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|18\n|-\n|Canada ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' Country\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955-1990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Country\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19691018.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles, October 18, 1969 |access-date=March 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330211252/http://tropicalglen.com/Archives/60s_files/19691018.html |archive-date=March